What I think is brought up here is a request for &quot;warning&quot; or 
&quot;soft-assertion&quot; level, which is lower than Failure or Error.
warn() should have the interface of assert(), except that it does not 
throw an exception, merely count it. It might still create a Throwable 
object (without throwing it), just to have  a stack-trace handy.






Vladimir Bossicard &lt;vladimir@...&gt;
24/07/2001 23:56
Please respond to junit


        To:     junit@yahoogroups.com
        cc: 
        Subject:        RE: [junit] Reporting more then 1 failed assertion per test


&gt; I think it would be useful in certain cases, sort of
&gt; like &quot;make -k&quot; (keep going if an error is found).

This is not possible with JUnit because JUnit throws an exception when an 
assertion is not &quot;true&quot;.  When an exception is thrown, &quot;the normal flow of 
the program is interrupted and that the runtime environment attempts to 
find an exception handler--a block of code that can handle a particular 
type of error.&quot; (Java Tutorial)  So the next assertion is not executed.

To &quot;correct&quot; that, you have to change the framework (record the errors and 
throw an exception at the end of the test method).  But I really don&#39;t 
think that this will solve problems:

   assertTrue(obj != null);
   assertTrue(obj.status() == 3);

if obj is null and you evaluate the next assert, the 
&quot;NullPointerException&quot; doesn&#39;t help much.

-Vladimir





